-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Show that for the side–lengths a, b, c of any triangle a²(b+c−a)+b²(c+a−b)+c²(a+b−c) ≤ 3abc. 2. [Key Idea] Replace the sides by Ravi variables a=y+z, b=z+x, c=x+y (x,y,z>0); the inequality turns into a symmetric homogeneous one that collapses to (x+y+z)(xy+yz+zx) ≥ 9xyz, an immediate consequence of AM–GM. 3. [Proof] Ravi substitution a=y+z, b=z+x, c=x+y (x,y,z>0). Left–hand side a²(b+c−a)+b²(c+a−b)+c²(a+b−c) =2[x(y+z)²+y(z+x)²+z(x+y)²]. (1) Right–hand side 3abc=3(x+y)(y+z)(z+x). (2) Inequality (1) ≤ (2) ⇔ 0 ≤ 3(x+y)(y+z)(z+x)−2[x(y+z)²+y(z+x)²+z(x+y)²]. (3) Use the identity (x+y)(y+z)(z+x)=(x+y+z)(xy+yz+zx)−xyz and (x+y+z)(xy+yz+zx)=∑ x²y+∑ xy²+3xyz. Substituting in (3) gives Δ = (x+y+z)(xy+yz+zx)−9xyz. (4) By the arithmetic–geometric mean inequality x+y+z ≥ 3√[3]{xyz}, xy+yz+zx ≥ 3√[3]{x²y²z²}=3(√[3]{xyz})², so (x+y+z)(xy+yz+zx) ≥ 9xyz, i.e. Δ ≥ 0. Hence (1) ≤ (2), proving the desired inequality. Equality occurs at x=y=z ⇔ a=b=c (the equilateral triangle). 4. [Conclusion] For every triangle, a²(b+c−a)+b²(c+a−b)+c²(a+b−c) never exceeds 3abc, with equality only for the equilateral case.
